<section id="poisson" class="page">
  <h2>Live Poisson model</h2>
  <p class="note">A goal-based scoreline model that updates as results come in. Each team starts with an attack and defence rating seeded from its pre-tournament goals and xG (with a luck-correction), then both ratings nudge gently after every completed match — cautiously early, more responsively as evidence builds. For each fixture it produces the most likely scorelines and win / draw / loss probabilities. The frozen pre-tournament composite prediction is shown alongside so you can see whether updating actually improves accuracy.</p>
  <div class="live-bar">
    <button id="poi-refresh">Refresh &amp; recompute</button>
    <span class="live-status" id="poi-status">Loading…</span>
  </div>
  <div class="cards" id="poi-cards"></div>
  <div class="sort-bar" id="poi-sortbar">
    <span>Sort</span>
    <button class="active" data-psort="pool">Pool</button>
    <button data-psort="date">Date</button>
    <span style="margin-left:10px">Show</span>
    <button class="active" data-pfilter="upcoming">Upcoming</button>
    <button data-pfilter="all">All fixtures</button>
    <button data-pfilter="played">Played</button>
  </div>
  <div id="poi-list"></div>
  <p class="live-src">Model runs entirely in your browser. Updates use final scores from the openfootball feed (goals, with shrinkage toward expectation to limit finishing luck). Not a full Dixon-Coles refit — see Methodology.</p>
</section>
<section id="method" class="page">
  <h2>How the model works</h2>
  <p class="note">Every number in this dashboard traces back to four variables, each normalised to a 0–1 scale and combined with fixed weights.</p>
  <div style="background:var(--panel);border:1px solid var(--gold);border-radius:12px;padding:22px;margin-bottom:26px">
    <div style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:14px;color:var(--gold)">Composite Score = (ELO × 0.45) + (Form × 0.25) + (xG Diff × 0.20) + (Squad Value × 0.10)</div>
    <p style="color:var(--muted);font-size:13px;margin-top:10px">For teams with fewer than 5 matches of xG data (Iran, Cape Verde, Uzbekistan), xG is excluded and the weights are redistributed proportionally: ELO 56.25% · Form 31.25% · Squad 12.5%. Host nations U.S.A., Canada and Mexico receive +0.073, derived from the standard +100 ELO point home advantage used by professional models.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="method-block">
    <h3 style="font-family:'Archivo';font-weight:800;text-transform:uppercase;font-size:15px;color:var(--elo);margin-bottom:8px">1 · ELO rating — 45%</h3>
    <p style="margin-bottom:10px">Current ELO ratings from eloratings.net, the strongest single predictor of international football outcomes. ELO adjusts after every match based on result, margin and opponent strength, so it implicitly captures a team's full competitive history. Normalised across the 48 qualified teams: <span style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace">(ELO − min) / (max − min)</span>.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="method-block">
    <h3 style="font-family:'Archivo';font-weight:800;text-transform:uppercase;font-size:15px;color:var(--form);margin:20px 0 8px">2 · Recent form score — 25%</h3>
    <p style="margin-bottom:10px">Built from each team's last 10 internationals (minimum 4 competitive matches; selection adjusted where needed). Each match produces a score from two components:</p>
    <div style="background:var(--bg2);border-radius:8px;padding:14px;font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace;font-size:12px;line-height:1.9;margin-bottom:10px;color:var(--text)">
      Component 1 = (Capped GD × 0.4 + Venue Adj × 0.4) × OW × Importance × Time Decay<br>
      Component 2 = Base Score × OW² × Importance × Time Decay<br>
      Match Score = Component 1 + Component 2
    </div>
    <ul style="padding-left:18px;line-height:1.8">
      <li><b style="color:var(--text)">Capped GD</b> — goal difference capped at ±3 so blowouts don't dominate</li>
      <li><b style="color:var(--text)">Base score</b> — Win 1, Draw 0.5, Loss 0, so draws never zero out</li>
      <li><b style="color:var(--text)">Opponent weight (OW)</b> — opponent ELO ÷ 1500, squared in component 2; inverted (1/OW) for losses so losing to weak teams is punished harder</li>
      <li><b style="color:var(--text)">Importance</b> — WC/Copa América 1.5, AFC Asian Cup 1.4, AFCON/Gold Cup 1.3, WC qualifier 1.2, Nations League 1.1, friendlies 0.7–0.8</li>
      <li><b style="color:var(--text)">Venue adjustment</b> — away +0.1, home −0.1, neutral 0</li>
      <li><b style="color:var(--text)">Time decay</b> — EXP(−0.1 × months ago); a match a year old keeps ~30% of its weight</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="margin-top:8px">The form score is the sum of all 10 match scores, then normalised across the 48 teams.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="method-block">
    <h3 style="font-family:'Archivo';font-weight:800;text-transform:uppercase;font-size:15px;color:var(--xg);margin:20px 0 8px">3 · xG differential — 20%</h3>
    <p style="margin-bottom:10px">Average expected-goals difference per match over the same 10-match window: <span style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace">AVG(xG for − xG against)</span>. xG measures the quality of chances created and conceded independent of results — it filters out finishing luck. No time decay or opponent weighting: chance quality is structurally stable and already partly self-adjusts for opposition. Data from Flashscore (Opta model). Matches without xG data are excluded from the average; teams with fewer than 5 data points are excluded from this variable entirely.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="method-block">
    <h3 style="font-family:'Archivo';font-weight:800;text-transform:uppercase;font-size:15px;color:var(--squad);margin:20px 0 8px">4 · Squad value — 10%</h3>
    <p style="margin-bottom:10px">Total squad market value from Transfermarkt, normalised across the 48 teams. A proxy for overall squad quality and depth. Deliberately low-weighted because it correlates heavily with ELO. Team profiles also show average age (peak window 26–29), attack/defence value ratio and midfield share of total value as context.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="method-block">
    <h3 style="font-family:'Archivo';font-weight:800;text-transform:uppercase;font-size:15px;color:var(--gold);margin:20px 0 8px">Match predictions, confidence &amp; live tracking</h3>
    <p style="margin-bottom:10px">The predicted winner is the team with the higher composite score; a gap below 0.08 is flagged "too close to call". The confidence score combines four signals: composite gap (40%), xG inclusion for both teams (25%), xG data quality (15%) and agreement with the betting market (20%). Confidence measures how reliable the prediction is — it is not a win probability.</p>
    <p style="margin-bottom:10px">Live results are pulled from the openfootball public-domain dataset and compared automatically: a predicted winner that wins counts as correct, a draw counts as half credit (the same convention as the 2022 backtest), and "too close to call" matches are tracked separately.</p>
    <p>Validation: ELO alone correctly predicted 54% of 2022 WC group matches (65% with half-credit draws), beating random chance (33%) and matching academic benchmarks. Venue coordinates on match cards were added during the dashboard build and are approximate stadium locations.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="method-block">
    <h3 style="font-family:'Archivo';font-weight:800;text-transform:uppercase;font-size:15px;color:var(--xg);margin:20px 0 8px">Live Poisson model</h3>
    <p style="margin-bottom:10px">Each team carries an <b style="color:var(--text)">attack</b> and <b style="color:var(--text)">defence</b> rating on a goals scale (1.0 = tournament average). Priors are seeded from pre-tournament goals-for / goals-against per match, corrected toward each team's xG so finishing luck in the warm-ups doesn't inflate them. Expected goals for a fixture = baseline (1.30) × attacker's attack × opponent's defence, with a 1.10 home factor for host nations. Those two expected-goal numbers feed independent Poisson distributions whose product gives the full scoreline grid; summing the grid yields win / draw / loss and expected points.</p>
    <p style="margin-bottom:10px"><b style="color:var(--text)">Updating:</b> after each completed match both teams' ratings move toward what happened, via <span style="font-family:'IBM Plex Mono',monospace">new = old + k × (shrunk_result − expected)</span>. The result is first shrunk toward its expectation to dampen flukes, and the learning rate k grows from ~0.04 early to ~0.10 later, so single group-stage games barely move ratings while accumulated knockout evidence counts more. This is a deliberately gentle, browser-side approximation — not Python's full maximum-likelihood Dixon-Coles refit, which would model low-score draw correlation and fit all parameters jointly.</p>
  </div>
</section>
</div>

